{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480971"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:54:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:54:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"132"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/132"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.75,0.11,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"132"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77137"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/132"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-09-26T01:35:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T09:47:41+10:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2021-07-10T07:17:34+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-22 17:25:43"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"132"}},"updatedBy":{"data":null},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62643"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5883"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41924"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62643"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77137"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by police who found him wandering confused. He has no identification and cannot provide any history. He does not take any known medications and his medical history is unknown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unkempt. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Blood glucose is 10.9 mmol/L (4.0-7.8). He is confused and disorientated to time, place, and person with inappropriate responses to questions. His speech is incoherent but there is no dysphasia. He has a right lateral gaze palsy and is markedly ataxic with an uncoordinated, staggering gait. He moves all limbs spontaneously and has normal reflexes throughout, though full neurological examination is limited by his confusion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alcoholic hallucinosis","Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy","Diabetic ketoacidosis","Cerebellar tumour","Brainstem infarct"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of \u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke\u0027s encephalopathy: \u003C/strong\u003Econfusion, oculomotor dysfunction (right lateral gaze palsy), and ataxia. This is a result of chronic alcohol use, with resulting thiamine deficiency and requires immediate treatment with thiamine replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcoholic hallucinosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with auditory hallucinations in a clear sensorium, without the characteristic findings of oculomotor dysfunction or ataxia seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause confusion, but would typically present with other features such as Kussmaul breathing, dehydration, and significantly elevated blood glucose. The patient\u0027s blood glucose of 10.9 mmol/L, while elevated, is not consistent with DKA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebellar tumour\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the ataxia but would not account for the acute confusion and oculomotor findings. Additionally, other posterior fossa signs such as headache and vomiting would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrainstem infarct\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the gaze palsy and ataxia but would typically present with other brainstem signs such as cranial nerve palsies or long tract signs. The acute confusion and context of alcohol use make Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy more likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy is characterised by the clinical triad of confusion, oculomotor dysfunction, and ataxia.","Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy is a medical emergency requiring immediate thiamine administration.","Chronic alcohol use is the most common risk factor for Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy in developed countries."],"references":["Ota Y, Capizzano AA, Moritani T, Naganawa S, Kurokawa R, Srinivasan A. Comprehensive review of Wernicke encephalopathy: pathophysiology, clinical symptoms and imaging findings. Jpn J Radiol. 2020 Sep;38(9):809-820. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32390125/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62643"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"132"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62643","links":{"self